## Known Issues & Lessons Learned

### kubeadm Certificate Renewal
- Certificates expire after 1 year by default
- Check: `kubeadm certs check-expiration` (run on control plane node)
- Renew: `kubeadm certs renew all` then restart control plane components
- After renewal, update kubeconfig: `cp /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf ~/.kube/config`
- Monitor via Prometheus: `(kubelet_certificate_manager_server_ttl_seconds / 86400) < 30`

### etcd Maintenance
- etcd runs on all 3 control plane nodes (stacked topology)
- Check health: `kubectl -n kube-system exec etcd-kube501 -- etcdctl endpoint health --cacert /etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/ca.crt --cert /etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/server.crt --key /etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/server.key`
- Quorum requires 2 of 3 nodes — losing 2 control plane nodes loses the cluster
- Defrag periodically: `etcdctl defrag` if DB size grows large
- Snapshot for backup: `etcdctl snapshot save /tmp/etcd-backup.db`

### containerd Issues
- If containerd hangs: `systemctl restart containerd` then `systemctl restart kubelet`
- Check crictl: `crictl ps` to see running containers
- Image cleanup: `crictl rmi --prune` to remove unused images

### CoreDNS
- Runs as Deployment in kube-system namespace (usually 2 replicas)
- If DNS resolution fails inside pods: check CoreDNS pods first
- Common fix: `kubectl rollout restart deployment/coredns -n kube-system`
- Check upstream: CoreDNS forwards to dns01 (192.168.1.2) or pihole (192.168.1.9)

### Node Pressure
- MemoryPressure: kubelet starts evicting pods — find the memory hog
- DiskPressure: usually /var/lib/containerd filling up — prune images
- PIDPressure: rare — check for fork bombs or runaway processes
- When pressure detected: `kubectl describe node <name>` for conditions and events

